<Page x:Class="AsynAwaitExamples.Steps.Step03_ReturningValues"
      xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
      xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
      Title="Step 3 - Returning Values">
    <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
        <StackPanel Margin="10">
            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource HeaderStyle}" 
                       Text="Step 3: Returning Values from Async Methods"/>

            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource ExplanationStyle}" xml:space="preserve">RETURNING DATA: Async methods can return values using Task&lt;T&gt;.

A normal method returns "int" or "string" directly.
An async method wraps the return value in a Task: "Task&lt;int&gt;" or "Task&lt;string&gt;".

When you "await" a Task&lt;string&gt;, you get the string out of it.
Think of Task&lt;string&gt; like a gift box. "await" unwraps it to get the string inside.

Example:
   Task&lt;string&gt;  -- await --  string
   Task&lt;int&gt;     -- await --  int
   Task          -- await --  (nothing, just waits for completion)</TextBlock>

            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="Fetch simulated data (returns a value)"
                    Click="FetchData_Click"/>

            <TextBox x:Name="Output" Style="{StaticResource OutputStyle}" Height="300"/>
        </StackPanel>
    </ScrollViewer>
</Page>
